  <h4><span class="sqsrte-text-color--custom"><strong>How We Can Help</strong></span></h4><h4><strong>Maintaining Status (Visitor Record)</strong></h4><p class="sqsrte-large">If your visa is about to expire or has already expired, contact us to assess your situation and assist you with applying to maintain your status, if eligible.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Study in Canada</title><dc:creator>Sara Naghedi-Ahmadi</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 21 Feb 2024 19:23:17 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.naghedi-immigration.ca/temporary-residence1/study-in-canada1</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6593abc53b38c97cdaf5a338:65d61ce73aa51c1190ef4132:65d64d76abf44a224168fdeb</guid><description><![CDATA[What is a Study Permit? The study permit is a document issued to enable 
foreign nationals to pursue studies at designated learning institutions 
(DLIs) in Canada.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class=""><br></p><h4><strong>What is a Study Permit?</strong> </h4><p class="sqsrte-large">The study permit is a document issued to eligible applicants and allows them to pursue studies at Designated Learning Institutions (DLIs) in Canada. </p><p class="sqsrte-large">You are considered a student if you've been given permission to enter and stay in Canada for your studies. Most individuals from other countries require a study permit to engage in studies in Canada. </p><p class="sqsrte-large">Study permit is not equivalent to a visa and does not grant entry into Canada. Therefore, in addition to the study permit, you may also be required to obtain a visitor visa or an electronic travel authorization (eTA). </p>





















  
  



